                    MFEM-SAMRAI Interoperability Examples

This directory contains examples demonstrating interoperability between MFEM
and SAMRAI (Structured Adaptive Mesh Refinement Application Infrastructure).

===============================================================================

Example 16: MFEM-SAMRAI Coupled Simulation
-------------------------------------------

Description:
  This example demonstrates basic interoperability between MFEM and SAMRAI by
  running both solvers side-by-side in an alternating time loop.

  MFEM Component:
    - Solves the nonlinear heat equation: du/dt = C(u)
    - C(u) = ∇·((κ + α*u) ∇u) - nonlinear diffusion operator
    - Uses unstructured mesh (read from file)
    - Implicit time integration with SDIRK methods

  SAMRAI Component:
    - Solves linear advection: du/dt + div(a*u) = 0
    - Uses structured Cartesian AMR grid
    - Explicit hyperbolic integration
    - Adaptive mesh refinement with Berger-Rigoutsos clustering

  Integration:
    - Both solvers advance in an alternating time loop
    - No data exchange in this version (loose coupling)
    - Demonstrates that MFEM and SAMRAI can coexist in the same program
    - Foundation for future examples with actual data coupling

Build Requirements:
  - MFEM with SAMRAI support: MFEM_USE_SAMRAI=ON
  - MFEM with MPI support: MFEM_USE_MPI=ON (required by SAMRAI)
  - SAMRAI library installed with HDF5 support (for visualization)
  - Optional: HYPRE (may be auto-fetched with MFEM_FETCH_TPLS=ON)

  Example CMake configuration:
    cmake .. \
      -DMFEM_USE_SAMRAI=ON \
      -DMFEM_USE_MPI=ON \
      -DSAMRAI_DIR=/path/to/samrai \
      -DMFEM_FETCH_TPLS=ON

  Then build:
    make samrai_ex16

Running:
  The example can run in serial or parallel with MPI.

  2D case (serial):
    ./ex16 -m ../data/inline-quad.mesh -i samrai_input.2d

  3D case (serial):
    ./ex16 -m ../data/star.mesh -i samrai_input.3d

  Parallel execution:
    mpirun -np 4 ./ex16 -m ../data/inline-quad.mesh -i samrai_input.2d

  Command-line options:
    -m <mesh>     MFEM mesh file (default: ../data/star.mesh)
    -r <levels>   Number of uniform refinements (default: 2)
    -o <order>    Finite element order (default: 2)
    -s <solver>   ODE solver type (default: 23 = SDIRK33)
    -tf <time>    Final time (default: 0.5)
    -dt <step>    Time step (default: 0.01)
    -a <alpha>    Alpha coefficient (default: 0.01)
    -k <kappa>    Kappa coefficient (default: 0.5)
    -i <input>    SAMRAI input file (default: samrai_input.3d)
    -vis/-no-vis  Enable/disable GLVis visualization (default: on)
    -visit        Enable VisIt data file output (default: off)
    -vs <steps>   Visualization frequency (default: 5)

Output:
  MFEM output files:
    - ex16.mesh         : MFEM mesh file
    - ex16-init.gf      : Initial temperature field
    - ex16-final.gf     : Final temperature field

    View with GLVis:
      glvis -m ex16.mesh -g ex16-final.gf

  SAMRAI output (if HDF5 available):
    - visit_samrai_2d/  : VisIt data files for 2D case
    - visit_samrai_3d/  : VisIt data files for 3D case

    View with VisIt:
      visit -o visit_samrai_3d/dumps.visit

  Both visualizations show the independent evolution of each solver:
    - MFEM: Heat diffusion with nonlinear conductivity
    - SAMRAI: Advecting sphere with AMR tracking the feature

Notes:
  - SAMRAI requires MPI, so MFEM must be built with MPI support
  - The two solvers operate on independent meshes (no geometric coupling)
  - Time steps are independent (no synchronization required)
  - This demonstrates "loose coupling" as a foundation for future work
  - For actual physics coupling, data transfer between solvers is needed

Future Extensions:
  - Add data transfer between MFEM and SAMRAI grids
  - Couple the physics problems (e.g., heat affects advection velocity)
  - Use SAMRAI's AMR to drive MFEM mesh refinement
  - Solve on overlapping or coincident domains
  - Implement tighter time step synchronization

===============================================================================

For general MFEM information and documentation, see https://mfem.org
For SAMRAI information, see https://computing.llnl.gov/projects/samrai
